Why? It will help in the early diagnosis of serious illness and doctors will be able to react early potentially saving people s lives Science site Wired UK reported this week.The University of Adelaide Australia used artificial intelligence to analyse images and determined with 69% accuracy which patients would die within five years.It s not so much about diagnosis but about predicting medical outcomes.Lead author Dr Luke Oakden-Rayner of the university s School of Public Health said: Predicting the future of a patient is useful because it may enable doctors to tailor treatments to the individual."In the study published in the Nature journal Scientific Reports the researchers said the most confident predictions were made for people with severe chronic diseases such as emphysema and congestive heart failure.